'''Laura Secord''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|s|iː|k|ɔɹ|d}} {{respell|SEE|kord}};<ref>{{cite video |title=Heritage Minutes: Laura Secord
 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_L-vL5NFkYA |publisher=[[Historica Canada]] |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BpfTD3DWxu0&t=44s |title=1812 - Part 2 - The Story of Laura Secord |accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> {{nee}} '''Ingersoll'''; 13 September 1775&nbsp;– 17 October 1868) was a Canadian heroine of the [[War of 1812]].  She is known for having walked {{convert|20|miles|km}} out of American-occupied territory in 1813 to warn British forces of an impending American attack.  Her contribution to the war was little known during her lifetime, but since her death she has been frequently honoured in Canada.  Though Secord had no relation to it, most Canadians associate her with the [[Laura Secord Chocolates]] company, named after her on the centennial of her walk.

Laura Secord's father, Thomas Ingersoll, lived in [[Province of Massachusetts Bay|Massachusetts]] and fought on the side of the [[Patriot (American Revolution)|Patriots]] during the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]] (1775–1783).  In 1795 he moved his family to the Niagara region of [[Upper Canada]] after he had applied for and received a land grant.  Shortly after, Laura married [[United Empire Loyalist|Loyalist]] James Secord, who was later seriously wounded at the [[Battle of Queenston Heights]] early in the War of 1812.  While he was still recovering in 1813, the Americans invaded the [[Niagara Peninsula]], including [[Queenston, Ontario|Queenston]].  During the occupation, Secord acquired information about a planned American attack, and stole away on the morning of 22 June to inform Lieutenant [[James FitzGibbon]] in the territory still controlled by the British.  The information helped the British and their [[Mohawk people|Mohawk]] warrior allies repel the invading Americans at the [[Battle of Beaver Dams]].  Her effort was forgotten until 1860, when [[Edward VII|Edward, Prince of Wales]] awarded the impoverished widow £100 for her service on his visit to Canada.<!-- the Canadian Pound lasted until 1858.  Should it be assumed this is the British pound? -->

The story of Laura Secord has taken on mythological overtones in Canada.  Her tale has been the subject of books, plays, and poetry, often with many embellishments.  Since her death, Canada has bestowed honours on her, including schools named after her, monuments, a museum, a memorial stamp and coin, and a statue at the [[Valiants Memorial]] in [[Ottawa|the Canadian capital]].

{{TOC limit|3}}

==Personal history==

===Family history and early life===

[[Thomas Ingersoll]] (1749–1812) married the seventeen-year-old Elizabeth Dewey on 28 February 1775.  Their first child, Laura, was born in [[Great Barrington, Massachusetts|Great Barrington]] in the colonial [[Province of Massachusetts Bay]] on 13 September 1775.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=16}}  Thomas's family had lived in Massachusetts for five generations.  He was descended from Richard Ingersoll, who had arrived in [[Salem, Massachusetts]], from [[Bedfordshire]], England, in 1629.  Thomas was born in 1749 in [[Westfield, Massachusetts]].  Elizabeth, daughter of Israel Dewey,{{sfn|Currie|1900|p=49}} was also born in Westfield,{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=16}} on 28 January 1758.{{sfnm|1a1=Currie|1y=1900|1p=49|2a1=Leavey|2y=2012|2p=16}}  Thomas moved to Great Barrington in 1774, where he settled into a house on a small piece of land by the [[Housatonic River]].  Over the next several years, his success as a [[Hatmaking|hatmaker]] allowed him to increase his landholdings and expand his house as his family grew.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|pp=16–17}}  He spent much time away from home, as he rose through the ranks in the military on the side of the [[patriot (American Revolution)|American revolutionaries]] during the [[American Revolutionary War]].  Upon his return to Great Barrington, he was made a [[magistrate]].{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=25}}

Elizabeth gave birth to three more girls: Elizabeth Franks on 17 October 1779; Mira (or Myra) in 1781; and Abigail in September 1783.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=19}}  Abigail was given up for adoption in 1784 to an aunt with the surname Nash.{{sfnm|1a1=Currie|1y=1900|1pp=49–50|2a1=Leavey|2y=2012|2pp=15–16, 24}}  Elizabeth Ingersoll died 20 February 1784,{{sfn|Currie|1900|p=50}} and Thomas remarried to Mercy Smith, widow of Josiah Smith,{{sfn|Currie|1900|p=50}} on 26 May 1785.  Mercy had no children.  She has been credited with teaching her stepdaughters to read and do [[needlework]] before her death from [[tuberculosis]] in 1789.  By adolescence, Laura was caring for her sisters and looking after the household affairs.  Thomas remarried four months after Mercy's death, on 20 September 1789, to Sarah "Sally" Backus, a widow with a daughter, Harriet.  The couple had a further four girls and three boys.  The first boy, Charles Fortescue, was born on 27 September 1791.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|pp=24–26}}  Charlotte (born 1793) and Appolonia (born 1794) were the last members of this branch of the Ingersoll family to be born in Massachusetts.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=31}}

Thomas helped suppress [[Shays' Rebellion]] in 1786, which earned him the rank of [[major (United States)|major]], but in the years following, he witnessed and was offended by the continuing [[Expulsion of the Loyalists#Attacks on Royal officials and Loyalists|persecution of Loyalists]].  He realized that in the depressed economic conditions that followed the Revolutionary War, and with his own deep debts, he was unlikely to see his former prosperity again.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|pp=26–27}}  In 1793, Thomas met in [[New York City]] with [[Mohawk people|Mohawk]] leader [[Joseph Brant]], who offered to show him the best land for settlement.  He and four associates travelled to [[Upper Canada]] to petition Lieutenant Governor [[John Graves Simcoe|John Simcoe]] for a land grant.  They received {{convert|66000|acre|ha sqmi|lk=on}} in the [[Thames Valley]], and founded Oxford-on-the-Thames (later known as [[Ingersoll, Ontario]]), on condition that they populate it with forty other families within seven years.  After winding up their affairs in Great Barrington, the Ingersoll family moved to Upper Canada in 1795.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|pp=29–31}}

===Upper Canada, marriage and children===

Thomas Ingersoll supported his family in their early years in Upper Canada by running a tavern in Queenston while land was being cleared and roads built in the settlement.  The family stayed in Queenston until a log cabin was completed on the settlement in 1796.  After Simcoe returned to England in 1796, opposition grew in Upper Canada to the "Late Loyalists" such as Thomas who had arrived in Canada for the land grants.  The grants were greatly reduced, and Thomas's contract was cancelled for not having all of its conditions fulfilled.  Feeling cheated, in 1805 he moved the family to [[Credit River]], close to York (present-day [[Toronto]]), where he successfully ran an inn until his 1812 death following a stroke.  Sally continued to run it until her own death in 1833.{{sfnm|1a1=Leavey|1y=2012|1pp=33, 35–37, 47|2a1=McKenzie|2y=1977|2p=29}}

Laura remained in Queenston when the family moved.  She married the wealthy James Secord, likely in June 1797.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=42}}{{efn|The exact date has not been determined as the marriage records were destroyed when the town was burned by the Americans in July 1814.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=42}} }}  The Secord family originated in France, where the name was spelled ''D'Secor'' or ''Sicar''.  Five Secord brothers, who were Protestant [[Huguenot]]s, fled from persecution in France and founded [[New Rochelle, New York]] in 1688.  At the time of the American Revolution, Loyalist members of the family [[Anglicisation|anglicized]] their surname to ''Secord''.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|pp=41–42}}

The Secord couple lived in a house built in <!-- no apostrophe in St. Davids -->[[Niagara-on-the-Lake|{{not a typo|St. Davids}}]],<!-- no apostrophe in St. Davids --> the first floor of which was a shop.  Secord gave birth to her first child, Mary, in St. {{not a typo|Davids}} in 1799.  Mary was followed by Charlotte (1801), Harriet (10 February 1803),{{sfn|Leavey|2012|pp=42–43}} Charles Badeau (1809—the only male child) and Appolonia (1810).{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=46}}

===War of 1812===

James Secord served in the [[The Lincoln and Welland Regiment|1st Lincoln Militia]]{{sfn|Firth|1966|p=180}} under [[Isaac Brock]] when the [[War of 1812]] broke out.  He was among those who helped carry away Brock's body after Brock was killed in the first attack of the [[Battle of Queenston Heights]] in October 1812.  James himself was severely wounded in the leg and shoulder during the battle.  Laura heard of his predicament and rushed to his side.  Some sources suggest that she found three American soldiers preparing to beat him to death with their gunstocks.  She begged them to save her husband's life, reportedly offering her own in return, when American Captain [[John E. Wool]] happened upon the situation and reprimanded the soldiers.{{sfnm|1a1=Bryce|1y=1907|1p=7|2a1=McKenzie|2y=1977|2p=15}}  This story may have been a later embellishment{{sfn|McKenzie|1977|p=15}} and may have originated with her grandson, James B. Secord.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|}}  When the Secords arrived home, they found that the house had been looted in Laura's absence.  Spending the winter in St. {{not a typo|Davids}},{{sfn|McKenzie|1977|p=16}} Laura spent the next several months nursing her wounded husband back to health.{{sfn|Karr|1938|pp=172–173}}

On 27 May 1813, the [[United States Army|American army]] launched [[Battle of Fort George|an attack]] across the Niagara River, and captured [[Fort George, Ontario|Fort George]].{{sfn|Collins|2006|p=109}}  Queenston and the Niagara area fell to the Americans.  Men of military age were sent as prisoners to the U.S., though the still-recuperating James Secord was not among them.  That June, a number of U.S. soldiers were [[billet]]ed at the Secords' home.{{sfnm|1a1=Karr|1y=1938|1pp=173–174|2a1=Bryce|2y=1907|2pp=9–10}}

===Secord's walk===

[[File:Laura Secord warns Fitzgibbons, 1813.jpg|thumb|alt=Painting of Laura Secord warning British commander James FitzGibbon of an impending American attack at Beaver Dams|Secord warns British commander [[James FitzGibbon]] of an [[Battle of Beaver Dams|impending American attack at Beaver Dams]] ([[Lorne Kidd Smith]], {{circa|1920}})]]

On the evening of 21 June,{{sfnm|1a1=Leavey|1y=2012|1p=89|2a1=Carstens|2a2=Sanford|2y=2011|2p=139|3a1=Richardson|3y=2006|3p=529|4a1=McKenzie|4y=2000|5a1=Jonasson|5y=2012}} Laura Secord heard of plans for a surprise American attack on British troops led by Lieutenant [[James FitzGibbon]] at Beaver Dams, which would have furthered American control in the [[Niagara Peninsula]].{{sfnm|1a1=Bryce|1y=1907|1pp=10–13|2a1=Carstens|2a2=Sanford|2y=2011|2p=139}}  It is unclear how she became aware of these plans.  According to tradition she overheard a conversation among the billeted Americans as they ate dinner.{{sfn|McKenzie|1977|pp=48–50}}  As her husband was still recovering from his October injuries, Secord set out herself early the next morning to warn the Lieutenant.  She reportedly walked {{convert|20|miles|km}} from present-day Queenston through St. {{not a typo|Davids}},{{efn|While in St. Davids, Secord stopped at the home of her half-brother Charles, who was ill in bed.{{sfn|McKenzie|1977|pp=52–54}} }} Homer, [[St. Catharines|Shipman's Corners]] and [[Pelham, Ontario|Short Hills]] at the [[Niagara Escarpment]] before she arrived at the camp of allied Mohawk warriors who led her the rest of the way to FitzGibbon's headquarters at the [[DeCou House|DeCew House]].  A small British force and a larger contingent of Mohawk warriors were then readied for the American attack.  Most of the American forces were casualties or taken prisoner in the [[Battle of Beaver Dams]] on 24 June.{{sfnm|1a1=Bryce|1y=1907|1pp=10–13|2a1=Carstens|2a2=Sanford|2y=2011|2p=139}}  No mention of Secord was made in reports that immediately followed the battle.{{sfnm|1a1=McKenzie|1y=1977|1p=70|2a1=Leavey|2y=2012|2p=112}}

===Post-war years===

After the war, with the Secords' Queenston store in ruins,{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=144}} the family was impoverished.  Only James's small war pension{{sfn|McKenzie|2000}} and the rent from 200 acres of land they had in [[Grantham Township, Ontario|Grantham Township]] supported them.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=144}}

The Secords' sixth child, Laura Anne, was born in October 1815, and their last child, Hannah, was born in 1817.  The Secords' eldest daughter Mary wedded a doctor, William Trumball, on 18 April 1816.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=144}}  On 27 March 1817, Mary gave birth in Ireland to Elizabeth Trumball, the first of Laura and James's grandchildren.  Mary had another daughter, also named Mary, in Jamaica, and brought her children back to Queenston with her in 1821 following her husband's death.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=146}}

[[File:Brocks Monument.jpg|left|thumb|alt=Painting with Brock's monument standing on the left side in a field, near a stone wall which runs diagonally along the bottom.|Secord was promised a position at [[Brock's Monument]], but the position was given to another woman. (1840 painting by Philip John Bainbrigge)]]

The struggling James petitioned the government in 1827 for some sort of employment.  Lieutenant-Governor [[Peregrine Maitland]] did not offer him a position, but offered something to Laura.  He asked her to be in charge of the yet-to-be-completed [[Brock's Monument]].  At first, she turned it down, but then reluctantly accepted it.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=148}}  When Brock's Monument opened in 1831,{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=150}} Secord learned the new Lieutenant-Governor, [[John Colborne, 1st Baron Seaton|John Colborne]], intended to give the keys to the widow of a member of the monument committee who had died in an accident.  On 17 July 1831, Secord petitioned Colborne to honour Maitland's promise, and included another certificate from FitzGibbon attesting her contribution to the war.  She wrote that Colonel Thomas Clarke had been told by Maitland, "it was too late to think of [the committee member's widow] Mrs. Nichol as I have pledged my word to Mrs. Secord that as soon as possible she should have the key."{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=151}}  Despite her pleas, Secord did not receive the keys to the monument.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=152}}

In 1828, the Secords' daughter, Appolonia, died at 18 of [[typhus]],{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=150}} and James was appointed registrar of the Niagara Surrogate Court.{{sfn|McKenzie|2000}}  He was promoted to judge in 1833,{{sfnm|1a1=McKenzie|1y=2000|2a1=Leavey|2y=2012|2p=155}} and his son Charles Badeau took over the registrar position.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=155}}  Charles Badeau's first son, Charles Forsyth Secord, was born 9 May 1833.  His is the only line of Secords that survived into the 21st century.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=157}}

James became a customs collector in 1835 at the port of Chippawa.{{sfnm|1a1=McKenzie|1y=2000|2a1=Leavey|2y=2012|2p=155|3a1=Currie|3y=1900|3p=69}}{{efn|Chippawa is now part of [[Niagara Falls, Ontario]].}}  The position came with a home in Chippawa, into which the family moved. Charles Badeau took over the Queenston home.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=156}}  Daughter Laura Ann and her son moved into the home in 1837 following her husband's death.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=168}}

===Later life and death===

[[File:Laura Secord statue.jpg|thumb|alt=Phot of a statue of a woman in a long dress and a bonnet.|Statue of Laura Secord at the [[Valiants Memorial]] in Ottawa]]

James Secord died of a stroke on 22 February 1841.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=165}}  He was buried, according to his wishes, at Drummond Hill (now in Niagara Falls).{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=165}}  James's death left Laura destitute.  His war pension came to an end,{{sfn|Leavey|2012|pp=164–165}} and she was unable to keep the land that she still had profitable, and sold off much of it.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=170}}  Governor-General [[Charles Poulett Thomson, 1st Baron Sydenham|Sydenham]] denied a 27 February 1841 petition she sent for her son to take over James's customs position.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|pp=166–167}}  Sydenham also denied a petition she sent that May for a pension for herself, as James had already received a pension for decades.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=167}}

Possibly with help from better-off members of the family, Secord moved to a red brick cottage on Water Street{{efn|Water Street has since been renamed Bridgewater Street.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=167}} }} in November 1841.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=167}}  Daughter Harriet and her own two daughters joined her in May 1842, after the alcohol poisoning death of Harriet's husband.  The three would stay with Secord for the rest of her life.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|pp=167–168}}  Youngest daughter Hannah also moved in when she was widowed in 1844, and brought two daughters with her.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=170}}  Though she lacked training, for a short time Secord ran a small school out of the home in an effort to support herself.  This venture came to an end when the public [[common school]] system was introduced{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=168}} in the 1840s.{{sfn|Gestwicki|Bertrand|2011|p=215}}

Over the years, the Secords unsuccessfully petitioned the government for some kind of acknowledgement. In 1860, when Secord was 85, the [[Edward VII|Prince of Wales]] heard of her story while travelling in Canada. At Chippawa, near Niagara Falls, he was made aware of Laura Secord's plight as an aging widow and sent an award of £100. It was the only official recognition that she received during her lifetime.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=11}}

Laura Secord died in 1868 at the age of 93.{{sfn|Carstens|Sanford|2011|p=140}}  She was interred next to her husband in the Drummond Hill Cemetery in Niagara Falls.{{sfn|Richardson|2006}}  Her grave is marked by a monument with a bust on top, and is close to a monument marking the [[Battle of Lundy's Lane]].{{sfn|Carstens|Sanford|2011|p=167}}  The inscription on her grave marker  reads:

{{quote|To perpetuate the name and fame of Laura Secord, who walked alone nearly 20 miles by a circuitous difficult and perilous route, through woods and swamps and over miry roads to warn a British outpost at DeCew's Falls of an intended attack and thereby enabled Lt. FitzGibbon on 24 June 1813, with fewer than 50 men of the H.M. 49th Regt., about 15 militiamen and a small force of Six Nations and other Indians under Capt. [[William Johnson Kerr]] and [[Dominique Ducharme]] to surprise and attack the enemy at Beechwoods (or Beaver Dams) and after a short engagement, to capture Col. Bosler of the U.S. Army and his entire force of 542 men with two field pieces.{{sfn|Coates|Morgan|2002|p=197}} }}

==Memory and legend==

Her granddaughter described Secord as being {{convert|5|ft|4|in|cm}} with brown eyes and a fair complexion.{{sfn|Currie|1900|p=73}}  James FitzGibbon wrote she was "of slight frame and delicate appearance".{{sfnm|1a1=Leavey|1y=2012|1p=96|2a1=Wilson|2y=2010}}  She was skilled at needlework, dressmaking and cooking.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=170}}  According to biographer Peggy Dymond Leavey, her many grandchildren enjoyed hearing their grandmother tell stories of her early life,{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=170}} and her Anglican{{sfn|Perkins|1989|p=166}} faith increased with age.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=169}}

In his report of the battle, FitzGibbon stated only that he "received information" about the threat; it is possible he omitted mention of Secord to protect her family during wartime.  He first wrote of Secord in a certificate dated 26 February 1820, in support of a petition by her husband for a licence to operate a stone quarry in Queenston.{{sfnm|1a1=McKenzie|1y=1977|1p=70|2a1=Leavey|2y=2012|2p=112}}  In 1827 FitzGibbon wrote:

{{Quote|text=I do hereby Certify that on the 22d. day of June 1813, Mrs. Secord, Wife of James Secord, Esqr. then of St. David's, came to me at the Beaver Dam after Sun Set, having come from her house at St. David's by a circuitous route a distance of twelve miles, and informed me that her Husband had learnt from an American officer the preceding night that a Detachment from the American Army then in Fort George would be sent out on the following morning (the 23d.) for the purpose of Surprising and capturing a Detachment of the 49th Regt. then at Beaver Dam under my Command.  In Consequence of this information, I placed the Indians under Norton together with my own Detachment in a Situation to intercept the American Detachment and we occupied it during the night of the 22d.&nbsp;– but the Enemy did not come until the morning of the 24th when his Detachment was captured.  Colonel Boerstler, their commander, in a conversation with me confirmed fully the information communicated to me by Mrs. Secord and accounted for the attempt not having been made on the 23rd. as at first intended.|sign=[[James FitzGibbon]]|source=letter dated 11 May 1827{{sfn|Moir|1964|p=313}} }}

[[File:Henry Sandham (1910) Laura Secord.jpg|left|thumb|alt=Painting of Laura Secord led by Mohawk warriors through the woods|left|Secord led through the woods by [[Mohawk people|Mohawks]] ([[Henry Sandham]], {{circa|1910}})]]

FitzGibbon wrote in a certificate dated 23 February 1837 that Secord did "acquaint" him with the Americans' intentions, but does not state whether he used the information.{{sfn|Cruikshank|1908|p=130}}  A diary entry of Mohawk chief [[John Norton (Mohawk chief)|John Norton]] talks of "a loyal Inhabitant {{interp|who}} brought information that the Enemy intended to attack", but does not name the "Inhabitant".{{sfn|Green|2013|p=6}}  [[Dominique Ducharme]], leader of the [[Kahnawake|Caughwanaga Mohawks]] in the Battle of Beaver Dams, made no mention of Secord in his reports, nor of receiving information from either Secord or FitzGibbon about the impending American attack.{{sfn|Green|2013|p=7}}

Secord wrote two accounts of her walk, the first in 1853,{{sfn|Cruikshank|1908|pp=127–128}} and the second in 1861.{{sfn|Wood|1920|pp=164–165}}  Neither account contains details that can be corroborated with military accounts of the battle, such as specific dates or details about troops.{{sfn|Green|2013|p=6}} Her account changed throughout her life.  Historian [[Pierre Berton]] noted that she never stated clearly how she learned of the impending attack.  She told FitzGibbon that her husband had learned about it from an American officer, but years later told her granddaughter that she had overheard the plans directly from the American soldiers billeted in her home. Berton suggested that Secord's informant could have been an American still residing in the United States, who would have been charged with [[treason]] had Secord revealed her source.{{sfn|Berton|1981|p=63}}  In the 1860s, as Secord's story gained prominence, historian William Foster Coffin added new details, which included the claim that Laura had brought a cow with her as an excuse to leave her home in case the American patrols questioned her.{{sfn|Morgan|1994}}

A number of writers have questioned Secord's story.  [[William Stewart Wallace|W. Stewart Wallace]], in his 1932 book, ''The Story of Laura Secord: A Study in Historical Evidence'', concluded her story was mostly myth, and that she played no significant role in the outcome of the Battle of Beaver Dams.  Historian George Ingram contended in his 1965 book ''The Story of Laura Secord Revisited'' that Secord's debunking had been taken too far.  Ruth MacKenzie also burnished Secord's reputation with ''Laura Secord: The Legend and the Lady'' in 1971.{{sfn|Knowles|1997|p=206}}

The question of Secord's actual contribution to the British success has been contested.  In the early 1920s, historians suggested that Native scouts had already informed FitzGibbon of the coming attack well before Secord had arrived on 23 June.{{sfn|Wood|1920|pp=65–66}} Historian Ernest Cruikshank wrote in 1895 that "Scarcely had Mrs Secord concluded her narrative, when [Ducharme's] scouts came in ... they had encountered the advance guard of  the enemy." {{sfn|Cruikshank|1895|p=15}} Later, two testimonials were found which FitzGibbon wrote in 1820 and 1827, which supported Secord's claim.  FitzGibbon asserted that Laura Secord had arrived on 22 June (not 23 June), and that "in consequence of this information" he had been able to intercept the American troops.{{sfn|McKenzie|2000}}

==Legacy==

[[File:Laura Secord Homestead, Niagara-on-the-Lake, Ontario.jpg|alt=A white house in three-quarter perspective.  In the foreground are several picnic benches.  To the left is a tall tree with a man standing beside it.  To the right, partly obsured by the house, is an old well.|thumb|Laura Secord Homestead in [[Queenston, Ontario|Queenston]] {{coord|43.16395|N|79.05523|W|region:CA}}]]

Historian Cecilia Morgan argues that the Secord story became famous in the 1880s when upper-class women sought to strengthen the emotional ties between Canadian women and the British Empire.  She writes that they needed a female heroine to validate their claims for [[women's suffrage]].{{sfn|Morgan|1994}}  The first product of their campaign was [[Sarah Anne Curzon]]'s verse drama ''Laura Secord: The Heroine of 1812'' in 1887.  The play was responsible for "a deluge of articles and entries on Secord that filled Canadian histories and school textbooks at the turn of the 20th century".{{sfn|Bird|2012}}  Although critics gave the play negative reviews, it was the first full work devoted to her story and popularized her image.{{sfn|Boyko-Head|2002|p=63}}

Secord has been compared to [[French-Canadian]] heroine [[Madeleine de Verchères]]{{sfnm|1a1=Karr|1y=1938|1p=172|2a1=Coates|2a2=Morgan|2y=2002|2p=3}} and to American Revolution hero [[Paul Revere]].{{sfn|Hunter|2012}}  Her story has been retold and commemorated by generations of biographers, playwrights, poets, novelists and journalists.{{sfn|Boyko-Head|2002|p=61}}

[[File:Laury Ingersoll Secord Monument db.jpg|left|upright|thumb|alt=An upright stone monument surrounded by a low hedge.  In the middle is an upright oval of an elderly woamn's face in relief.|Laura Secord Monument in [[Queenston Heights]] {{coord|43.160352|N|79.051103|W|region:CA}}]]

After she discovered a newspaper clipping of the story, early feminist Emma Currie  began a lifelong interest in Secord's life.  After she tracked down information from relatives as far away as Great Barrington, she published a biographical account in 1900 called ''The Story of Laura Secord'', and later successfully petitioned to have a Secord memorial erected in Queenston Heights.{{sfn|Dagg|2001}}  The [[Ashlar|cut stone]]{{sfn|Collins|2006|p=111}} granite monument stands {{convert|7|ft|cm}} and was dedicated in 1901.{{sfnm|1a1=Acton Free Press staff|1y=1901|2a1=Colombo|2y=1984|2p=163}}  In 1905, her portrait was hung in Parliament.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=189}}  Playwright [[Merrill Denison]] made a [[Radio drama|radio play]] of her story in 1931 which mixed serious history with parody.{{sfn|Boyko-Head|2002|p=61}}

On the centennial of her walk in 1913, and to capitalize on Canadian patriotic feelings, [[Frank Patrick O'Connor|Frank O'Connor]] founded [[Laura Secord Chocolates]].  The chain's first location opened on [[Yonge Street|Yonge]] and Elm Streets in Toronto.{{efn|The chain's first store opened 20 October 1913 at 354 Yonge Street.{{sfn|Bradburn|2013}} }}  The chocolates came in black boxes adorned with a [[cameo (carving)|cameo]] of Secord.{{sfnm|1a1=Boyko-Head|1y=2002|1pp=76–77|2a1=Carr|2y=2003|2pp=43–44|3a1=Jonasson|3y=2012}}  By the 1970s, the company had become the largest candy retailer in Canada.{{sfn|Carr|2003|p=117}}  Among most Canadians, the name Laura Secord is more strongly associated with the chocolate company than the historical figure.{{sfnm|1a1=Holmlund|1a2=Youngberg|1y=2003|1p=9|2a1=Coates|2a2=Morgan|2y=2002|2p=47}}

The Secords' Queenston homestead was fired upon and [[Looting|looted]] during the War of 1812.  Restored and given to the Niagara Parks Commission in 1971,{{sfnm|1a1=Carstens|1a2=Sanford|1y=2011|1p=140|2a1=Leavey|2y=2012|2p=213}} it is now a museum and gift shop at Partition and Queen streets in Queenston.{{sfn|Collins|2006|p=110}}  Thomas Ingersoll's old home on Main Street in Great Barrington, Massachusetts, was used as the town's Free Library from 1896 until 1913, after which the Mason Library was built on the site.{{sfn|Leveille|2011|p=12}}  The Great Barrington Historic District Commission made 18 October 1997 Laura Secord Day, and dedicated a plaque in her honour before Mason Library.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=196}}

[[File:Revised Laura Secord Logo.jpg|alt=Laura Sceords Chocolate logo|right|thumb|alt=Logo of the Laura Secord Chocolates company.  Across the middle is written "Laura Secord" in cursive script.  In the upper middle is an upright oval enclosing the face of a young woman.  Below is written "Depuis Since 1913.|[[Laura Secord Chocolates]] commemorated Secord on the centennial of her walk.]]

Laura Secord is the namesake of a number of schools, including Laura Secord Public School (also known as Laura Secord Memorial School,{{sfn|Colombo|1984|p=163}} 1914–2010){{sfn|Berry|2010}}<!-- both names point to 5 Walnut St. in Queenston --> in Queenston, École Laura Secord School in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]] (built 1912),{{sfn|Blanchard|2005|p=3}} and [[School District 39 Vancouver|Laura Secord Elementary School]] in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].  Beaver Dams Battlefield Park has a plaque dedicated to Secord.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=197}}  In 1992, Canada Post issued a Laura Secord commemorative stamp.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|p=214}}  In 2003, the [[Minister of Canadian Heritage]] declared Secord a "Person of National Historical Significance",{{sfn|Carstens|Sanford|2011|p=140}} and in 2006 Secord's was one of fourteen statues dedicated at the [[Valiants Memorial]] in Ottawa.{{sfn|Leavey|2012|pp=197–198}}  To commemorate the 200th anniversary of her walk, Secord's image adorned a circulation [[Quarter (Canadian coin)|quarter]] issued by the [[Royal Canadian Mint]]{{efn|The coin was part of a War of 1812 series.{{sfn|Fraser|2013}} }} and a postage stamp from [[Canada Post]].{{sfn|Fraser|2013}}

